<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920108-0062</DOCNO><DOCID>920108-0062.</DOCID><HL>   Labor Agency Acts   To Reclaim License   From North Carolina</HL><DATE>01/08/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><RE>NORTH CAROLINA (NC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department is moving towardfederal takeover of North Carolina's entire worker safety andhealth program.   Officials at the department said the agency's OccupationalSafety and Health Administration will give the state's labordepartment 90 days to achieve significant improvements in itsprogram or OSHA will revoke its approval of the entire stateplan.</LP><TEXT>   OSHA assumed authority for some important parts of thestate program in the wake of a fire in September that killed25 poultry-plant workers in Hamlet, N.C. OSHA now handles newworker health or safety complaints and complaints referred bystate officials. The federal agency also monitors stateinvestigations of catastrophes, including any accidents thatinvolve worker fatalities or the hospitalization of five ormore workers.   North Carolina is one of 25 states and territories thatrun state occupational safety and health programs underdelegated authority from OSHA. The federal agency directlyregulates programs in other states.</TEXT></DOC>